// Joint placement — host cut in a loop (regression). A loop whose pool is read by a HOST step every iteration
// (here `draw`, a CPU renderer reading P) is NOT resident across the back-edge: the pool round-trips every
// frame regardless of placement. So the joint pass must NOT treat the loop cluster as free-residency — a light
// map over that pool stays on the CPU (the transfer per frame dwarfs its tiny compute). This is the arche-rpg
// case: an 8-row `game.step` feeding a software renderer must be CPU, not wrongly forced to the GPU. The host
// cut is a COST, not a ban — a heavy enough map over the same pool would still win the GPU (covered by the
// cost model / the DP), but this light one does not. `make test-joint-placement` asserts `light` -> CPU with
// resident=0. Build-only (a `forever` loop never returns).
// RUN: %arche build -o %t %s
#import { fmt }
p :: float;
P :: arche { p }
[8]P(8);

seed :: system { P.p = { 1.0 }; }

light :: map (query { p }) (p) {
  p = p + 1.0;
}

draw :: system eff {
  fmt.printf("p=%.0f\n", P.p[0]);
}

#run seq({ seed, forever(seq({ light, draw })) })
